{
  "answer": "In the context of the one-sector model analyzed by Benhabib and Farmer, transversality conditions play a crucial role in ruling out explosive paths in the absence of externalities. These conditions ensure that the economy's state variables converge to their steady-state values over time, effectively eliminating paths that would otherwise diverge or explode. Here's how it works:\\n1. Transversality conditions are boundary conditions imposed on the dynamic optimization problem of agents in the economy. They require that the present discounted value of future marginal utilities of consumption approaches zero as time goes to infinity.\\n2. In the absence of externalities, the economy's dynamics are determined by the interaction between the labor demand and supply curves. When these curves exhibit non-standard slopes due to increasing returns, they can lead to multiple equilibria, some of which may be explosive.\\n3. By imposing transversality conditions, the model ensures that only those paths that converge to the steady state are considered feasible. This effectively rules out explosive paths, as they would violate the condition that the present discounted value of future marginal utilities approaches zero."
}

