{
  "answer": "Step 1: In a multiple regression model, we want to test the null hypothesis that all regression coefficients except the intercept are zero. This is a joint hypothesis because it involves more than one coefficient.\\nStep 2: The test statistic for this joint hypothesis is the F-statistic, which is calculated as the ratio of the mean regression sum of squares (MSS) to the mean error sum of squares (ESS).\\nStep 3: The MSS is calculated by dividing the regression sum of squares (RSS) by the number of coefficients being tested (k), which is also known as the degrees of freedom for the numerator. RSS measures the variability explained by the regression model.\\nStep 4: The ESS is calculated by dividing the error sum of squares (SSE) by the degrees of freedom for the error (n-k-1), where n is the sample size. SSE measures the variability not explained by the regression model.\\nStep 5: The F-statistic is then calculated as F = MSS / ESS.\\nStep 6: Under the null hypothesis, the F-statistic follows an F-distribution with (k, n-k-1) degrees of freedom, where k is the number of coefficients being tested and n is the sample size.\\" 
