{
  "answer": "To prove that if the Laspeyres index is less than 1, the consumer is better off in period 2, we need to understand what the Laspeyres index represents and how it relates to consumer welfare:\\nStep 1: Define the Laspeyres index. The Laspeyres index compares the cost of purchasing the same basket of goods in period 2 as was purchased in period 1, using period 1 quantities as weights. It is calculated as the ratio of the total cost of the period 1 basket at period 2 prices (C2) to the total cost of the period 1 basket at period 1 prices (C1).\\[ L = \\frac{C2}{C1} = \\frac{\\sum p_2 q_1}{\\sum p_1 q_1} \\]\\nStep 2: Interpret the meaning of the Laspeyres index being less than 1. If the Laspeyres index (L) is less than 1, it means that the cost of purchasing the period 1 basket at period 2 prices is lower than the cost of purchasing the same basket at period 1 prices. This implies that prices have decreased on average when weighted by the quantities consumed in period 1.\\[ L < 1 \\Rightarrow C2 < C1 \\Rightarrow \\frac{\\sum p_2 q_1}{\\sum p_1 q_1} < 1 \\]\\nStep 3: Relate the decrease in cost to consumer welfare. A decrease in the cost of purchasing the same basket of goods indicates that consumers can purchase the same goods for less money in period 2 compared to period 1. This improvement in purchasing power translates to higher consumer welfare or a better standard of living.\\[ C2 < C1 \\Rightarrow \\text{Consumer welfare in period 2 is greater than in period 1} \\]\\nConclusion: If the Laspeyres index is less than 1, it signifies that the cost of purchasing the same basket of goods has decreased, leading to improved consumer welfare and a better standard of living in period 2."
}

