{
  "answer": "To show that strong and weak Pareto efficiency are equivalent under strongly monotone preferences, we need to prove two directions: strong Pareto efficiency implies weak Pareto efficiency, and weak Pareto efficiency implies strong Pareto efficiency under strongly monotone preferences.\\nStep 1: Strong Pareto Efficiency Implies Weak Pareto Efficiency:\"a. Assume a feasible allocation (x, y) is strongly Pareto efficient.b. Take any allocation (x', y') for which ui(x'i) > ui(xi) for all i.c. By strong Pareto efficiency of (x, y), (x', y') cannot be feasible.d. Thus, (x, y) must also be weakly Pareto efficient since no feasible allocation makes everyone strictly better off.\"Step 2: Weak Pareto Efficiency Implies Strong Pareto Efficiency Under Strongly Monotone Preferences:\"a. Assume a feasible allocation (x, y) is not strongly Pareto efficient, i.e., there exists a feasible allocation (x', y') for which ui(x'i) ≥ ui(xi) for all i, and uk(x'k) > uk(xk) for some k.b. Since X1 = R+2 and preferences are strongly monotone, we must also have uk(x'k) > uk(xk) ≥ uk(0).c. Therefore, x'k ≠ 0, meaning x'ks > 0 for at least one commodity s.d. Under strongly monotone preferences, if an allocation is weakly Pareto efficient and there exists an allocation that makes someone strictly better off without making anyone else worse off, then the original allocation was not weakly Pareto efficient, leading to a contradiction.e. Hence, under strongly monotone preferences, weak Pareto efficiency implies strong Pareto efficiency."
}

{
  "answer": "A good point estimator should possess certain desirable properties, which include:

1. Unbiasedness: An estimator is considered unbiased if its expected value equals the true parameter value. Mathematically, this means E[\(\hat{\theta}\)] = \(\theta\). In the context of estimating the mean \(\mu\), if \(\bar{X}\) is an unbiased estimator, then E[\(\bar{X}\)] = \(\mu\).

2. Efficiency: Among all unbiased estimators, the most efficient estimator has the smallest variance. This means that it provides estimates that are tightly clustered around the true parameter value. The efficiency of an estimator can be quantified by comparing its variance to the variances of other unbiased estimators. A more efficient estimator will have a smaller variance, leading to more precise estimates."
