{
  "answer": "To prove that if a preference relation > is transitive and complete, then the induced indifference relation ~ is symmetric and transitive, we follow these steps:\\nStep 1: Define the indifference relation ~ as follows: x ~ y if and only if neither x > y nor y > x.\\nStep 2: Prove symmetry of ~. Suppose x ~ y. This means neither x > y nor y > x. By the completeness of >, either x > y, y > x, or x ~ y. Since x ~ y, it follows that y ~ x because neither y > x nor x > y. Hence, ~ is symmetric.\\nStep 3: Prove transitivity of ~. Suppose x ~ y and y ~ z. By definition, neither x > y nor y > x, and neither y > z nor z > y. We need to show that x ~ z, meaning neither x > z nor z > x. Assume for contradiction that x > z. Since y > z would contradict y ~ z, and similarly, z > y would contradict y ~ z, we must have y ~ z. But then, since x > z and z ~ y, by the transitivity of >, we would have x > y, which contradicts x ~ y. Similarly, assuming z > x leads to a contradiction. Therefore, neither x > z nor z > x, proving x ~ z. Hence, ~ is transitive."
