  "answer": "To prove that if $T \\sim t_n$, then $T^2 \\sim F_{1,n}$, we need to understand the definitions of the t and F distributions. The t-distribution with n degrees of freedom can be defined as the ratio of a standard normal variable Z and the square root of a chi-squared variable with n degrees of freedom, divided by n, where both Z and the chi-squared variable are independent. That is, if $Z \\sim N(0,1)$ and $V \\sim \\chi_n^2$, then $T = \\frac{Z}{\\sqrt{V/n}}$ follows a t-distribution with n degrees of freedom. Now, let's consider $T^2$. We have:\\n\\nStep 1: Express T^2 in terms of Z and V.\\n$T^2 = \\left(\\frac{Z}{\\sqrt{V/n}}\\right)^2 = \\frac{Z^2}{V/n} = \\frac{nZ^2}{V}$\\n\\nStep 2: Identify the distribution of Z^2.\\nSince $Z \\sim N(0,1)$, it follows that $Z^2 \\sim \\chi_1^2$. This is because the square of a standard normal variable follows a chi-squared distribution with 1 degree of freedom.\\n\\nStep 3: Apply the definition of the F-distribution.\\nGiven that $X_1 \\sim \\chi_{k_1}^2$ and $X_2 \\sim \\chi_{k_2}^2$ are independent, then $F = \\frac{(X_1/k_1)}{(X_2/k_2)}$ has an F-distribution with $(k_1, k_2)$ degrees of freedom. In our case, $X_1 = nZ^2$ and $X_2 = V$, with $k_1 = 1$ and $k_2 = n$. Therefore, $T^2 = \\frac{nZ^2}{V}$ follows an F-distribution with $(1, n)$ degrees of freedom.\\n\\nIn conclusion, if $T \\sim t_n$, then $T^2 \\sim F_{1,n}$."
}

