{
  "answer": "Single-peaked preferences prevent cyclical majorities due to their inherent structure, as outlined in Lemma C.4. Here's how:\\nStep 1: According to Definition C.2, single-peaked preferences mean there exists a peak point \\(\\theta^{h}\\) on the preference scale \\(\\Theta\\) for each individual. Preferences increase as one moves towards this peak and decrease moving away from it in either direction.\\nStep 2: When all preferences are single-peaked, it means every individual has a clear most preferred alternative and their preferences decline monotonically as they move away from this peak.\\nStep 3: Under majority voting, an alternative that is preferred by more individuals than any other alternative is known as a Condorcet winner. In the case of single-peaked preferences, there will always be at least one alternative that is preferred by a majority over any other alternative.\\nStep 4: This is because, given the monotonic nature of single-peaked preferences, there will be a point on the preference scale where the majority prefers alternatives closer to their peaks over those further away. This ensures that no cycle of preferences can emerge where each alternative is preferred over another in a loop, as would be possible under more complex preference structures.\\nStep 5: Therefore, according to Lemma C.4, majority voting under single-peaked preferences guarantees the existence of a unique Condorcet winner, eliminating the possibility of cyclical majorities."
}

