  "answer": "To derive the F-statistic for testing the restriction $\\beta_{2}+\\beta_{3}=1$ in the Cobb-Douglas production function, we need to compare the results of the unrestricted model to those of the restricted model. Here are the steps:\\nStep 1: Estimate the unrestricted model and obtain the residual sum of squares (RSS) and the coefficient of determination ($R^{2}$) denoted as $R_{\\mathrm{UR}}^{2}$.\\nStep 2: Impose the restriction $\\beta_{2}+\\beta_{3}=1$ on the model and estimate it using restricted least squares. Obtain the residual sum of squares (RSS) and the coefficient of determination ($R^{2}$) denoted as $R_{\\mathrm{R}}^{2}$.\\nStep 3: Calculate the difference between the $R^{2}$ values of the unrestricted and restricted models: $R_{\\mathrm{UR}}^{2}-R_{\\mathrm{R}}^{2}$.\\nStep 4: Divide the difference by the number of restrictions, m, which is 1 in this case since there is only one restriction being tested.\\nStep 5: Calculate the denominator of the F-statistic by dividing $(1-R_{\\mathrm{UR}}^{2})$ by the degrees of freedom of the unrestricted model, which is $(n-k)$, where n is the sample size and k is the number of parameters in the unrestricted model.\\nStep 6: The F-statistic is then calculated as the ratio of the result from Step 4 to the result from Step 5: $F=\\frac{(R_{\\mathrm{UR}}^{2}-R_{\\mathrm{R}}^{2})/m}{(1-R_{\\mathrm{UR}}^{2})/(n-k)}$. This provides the F-statistic for testing the specified restriction."
