{
  "answer": "Step 1: Monte Carlo tests and bootstrap tests are both simulation-based methods used to estimate the sampling distribution of a statistic and calculate p-values or confidence intervals when the theoretical distribution is unknown or complex.\\nStep 2: Monte Carlo tests, as described in the context, involve simulating data from a chosen distribution under the null hypothesis. This method assumes that the statistic is pivotal, meaning its distribution is the same for all distributions in the model under test. The simulations are used to construct an empirical distribution function (EDF) to approximate the true cumulative distribution function (CDF) of the test statistic under the null hypothesis.\\nStep 3: Bootstrap tests, on the other hand, do not assume a specific distribution under the null hypothesis. Instead, they resample the observed data with replacement to create new datasets. These datasets are used to estimate the sampling distribution of the statistic, making no assumptions about the underlying population distribution. This makes bootstrap tests more flexible but potentially less efficient than Monte Carlo tests when the pivotal assumption holds.\\nStep 4: In terms of applicability, Monte Carlo tests are suitable when the statistic is pivotal and the distribution under the null hypothesis is known or can be assumed. Bootstrap tests are more broadly applicable, especially when the distribution of the statistic under the null hypothesis is unknown or when the pivotal assumption does not hold."
