  "answer": "Step 1: Start with the first-order condition for the M-estimator, which is given by \\(\\frac{1}{n}\\sum_{t=1}^{n}\\mathbf{s}(\\mathbf{w}_{t};\\hat{\\pmb\\theta}) = \\mathbf{0}\\). This equation represents the condition that the derivative of the objective function with respect to \\(\\pmb\\theta\\) evaluated at the M-estimator \\(\\hat{\\pmb\\theta}\\) is zero.\\nStep 2: Apply the Mean Value Theorem to the vector-valued function \\(\\mathbf{s}(\\mathbf{w}_{t};\\pmb\\theta)\\). According to the Mean Value Theorem, there exists a point \\(\\tilde{\\pmb\\theta}\\) between \\(\\pmb\\theta_0\\) and \\(\\hat{\\pmb\\theta}\\) such that \\(\\mathbf{s}(\\mathbf{w}_{t};\\hat{\\pmb\\theta}) - \\mathbf{s}(\\mathbf{w}_{t};\\pmb\\theta_0) = \\mathbf{H}(\\mathbf{w}_{t};\\tilde{\\pmb\\theta})(\\hat{\\pmb\\theta} - \\pmb\\theta_0)\\), where \\(\\mathbf{H}(\\mathbf{w}_{t};\\tilde{\\pmb\\theta})\\) is the Hessian matrix of \\(\\mathbf{s}(\\mathbf{w}_{t};\\pmb\\theta)\\) evaluated at \\(\\tilde{\\pmb\\theta}\\).\\nStep 3: Take the expectation of both sides of the equation derived in Step 2. Since \\(\\mathbf{s}(\\mathbf{w}_{t};\\pmb\\theta_0)\\) has mean zero (by assumption), we get \\(\\mathbf{E}[\\mathbf{s}(\\mathbf{w}_{t};\\hat{\\pmb\\theta})] = \\mathbf{E}[\\mathbf{H}(\\mathbf{w}_{t};\\tilde{\\pmb\\theta})](\\hat{\\pmb\\theta} - \\pmb\\theta_0)\\). However, since \\(\\hat{\\pmb\\theta}\\) satisfies the first-order condition, \\(\\mathbf{E}[\\mathbf{s}(\\mathbf{w}_{t};\\hat{\\pmb\\theta})] = \\mathbf{0}\\), leading to \\(\\mathbf{0} = \\mathbf{E}[\\mathbf{H}(\\mathbf{w}_{t};\\tilde{\\pmb\\theta})](\\hat{\\pmb\\theta} - \\pmb\\theta_0)\\).\\nStep 4: Divide both sides of the equation from Step 3 by \\(\\sqrt{n}\\) and rearrange to get \\(\\sqrt{n}(\\hat{\\pmb\\theta} - \\pmb\\theta_0) = \\left(\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{n}}\\mathbf{E}[\\mathbf{H}(\\mathbf{w}_{t};\\tilde{\\pmb\\theta})]\\right)^{-1}\\mathbf{0}\\). By the consistency of \\(\\hat{\\pmb\\theta}\\) and the local dominance condition on the Hessian, \\(\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{n}}\\mathbf{E}[\\mathbf{H}(\\mathbf{w}_{t};\\tilde{\\pmb\\theta})]\\) converges in probability to \\(\\mathbf{E}[\\mathbf{H}(\\mathbf{w}_{t};\\pmb\\theta_0)]\\), which is nonsingular by assumption.\\nStep 5: By Slutsky's theorem, if \\(\\sqrt{n}(\\hat{\\pmb\\theta} - \\pmb\\theta_0)\\) converges in distribution to a random variable \\(Z\\) and \\(\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{n}}\\mathbf{E}[\\mathbf{H}(\\mathbf{w}_{t};\\tilde{\\pmb\\theta})]\\) converges in probability to a nonsingular matrix \\(\\mathbf{A}\\), then \\(\\mathbf{A}^{-1}Z\\) converges in distribution to a multivariate normal distribution with mean zero and covariance matrix \\(\\mathbf{A}^{-1}\\pmb\\Sigma\\mathbf{A}^{-1}\\), where \\(\\pmb\\Sigma\\) is the covariance matrix of \\(\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{n}}\\sum_{t=1}^{n}\\mathbf{s}(\\mathbf{w}_{t};\\pmb\\theta_0)\\). Therefore, \\(\\sqrt{n}(\\hat{\\pmb\\theta} - \\pmb\\theta_0)\\) converges in distribution to a multivariate normal distribution with mean zero and covariance matrix \\(\\left(\\mathbf{E}[\\mathbf{H}(\\mathbf{w}_{t};\\pmb\\theta_0)]\\right)^{-1}\\pmb\\Sigma\\left(\\mathbf{E}[\\mathbf{H}(\\mathbf{w}_{t};\\pmb\\theta_0)]\\right)^{-1}\\)."
