{
  "answer": "Step 1: The OLS estimator for \\(\\beta_1\\) is derived from minimizing the sum of squared residuals. The residual is defined as \\(e_i = y_i - \\hat{y}_i = y_i - (\\hat{\\beta}_0 + \\hat{\\beta}_1 x_i)\\). The sum of squared residuals is \\(S(\\hat{\\beta}_0, \\hat{\\beta}_1) = \\sum_{i=1}^{n} e_i^2\\). To find the estimator for \\(\\beta_1\\), we take the partial derivative of \\(S(\\hat{\\beta}_0, \\hat{\\beta}_1)\\) with respect to \\(\\hat{\\beta}_1\\) and set it equal to zero. This gives us the normal equation for \\(\\hat{\\beta}_1\\): \\[\\frac{\\partial S}{\\partial \\hat{\\beta}_1} = -2\\sum_{i=1}^{n} x_i(y_i - \\hat{\\beta}_0 - \\hat{\\beta}_1 x_i) = 0\\].\\nStep 2: Solving the normal equation for \\(\\hat{\\beta}_1\\) yields the expression for the OLS estimator of \\(\\beta_1\\): \\[\\hat{\\beta}_1 = \\frac{\\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i - \\bar{x})(y_i - \\bar{y})}{\\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i - \\bar{x})^2}\\], where \\(\\bar{x}\\) and \\(\\bar{y}\\) are the sample means of \\(x\\) and \\(y\\), respectively.\\nStep 3: To show that \\(E(\\hat{\\beta}_1) = \\beta_1\\), we need to take the expectation of \\(\\hat{\\beta}_1\\) and use the assumptions SLR.1-SLR.4. Using the linearity of expectation, we get: \\[E(\\hat{\\beta}_1) = E\\left(\\frac{\\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i - \\bar{x})(y_i - \\bar{y})}{\\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i - \\bar{x})^2}\\right)\\].\\nStep 4: Substitute the population model \\(y_i = \\beta_0 + \\beta_1 x_i + u_i\\) into the expectation: \\[E(\\hat{\\beta}_1) = E\\left(\\frac{\\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i - \\bar{x})(\\beta_0 + \\beta_1 x_i + u_i - \\bar{y})}{\\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i - \\bar{x})^2}\\right)\\].\\nStep 5: Simplify the numerator by separating the terms: \\[E(\\hat{\\beta}_1) = E\\left(\\frac{\\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i - \\bar{x})\\beta_0 + \\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i - \\bar{x})\\beta_1 x_i + \\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i - \\bar{x})u_i - \\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i - \\bar{x})\\bar{y}}{\\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i - \\bar{x})^2}\\right)\\].\\nStep 6: Note that \\(\\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i - \\bar{x})\\beta_0\\) and \\(-\\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i - \\bar{x})\\bar{y}\\) are both zero due to the properties of sample means. Also, \\(\\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i - \\bar{x})\\beta_1 x_i\\) simplifies to \\(\\beta_1\\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i - \\bar{x})^2\\). Thus, we have: \\[E(\\hat{\\beta}_1) = E\\left(\\frac{\\beta_1\\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i - \\bar{x})^2 + \\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i - \\bar{x})u_i}{\\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i - \\bar{x})^2}\\right)\\].\\nStep 7: The term \\(\\beta_1\\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i - \\bar{x})^2\\) cancels out with the denominator, leaving: \\[E(\\hat{\\beta}_1) = E\\left(\\frac{\\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i - \\bar{x})u_i}{\\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i - \\bar{x})^2}\\right)\\].\\nStep 8: By assumption SLR.3 (Zero Conditional Mean), \\(E(u|x) = 0\\), which implies that \\(E(x_iu_i) = 0\\) for all \\(i\\). Therefore, the expectation of the remaining term is zero: \\[E(\\hat{\\beta}_1) = \\beta_1\\]."
